    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1968-01-22T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1968-01-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="328"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d328">
                <head>328. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d328fn1"
                        >Source: Library of Congress Manuscript Division, Harriman Papers, <persName
                            corresp="#p_KRF1">Kennedy</persName> and <persName>Johnson</persName>
                        Administrations, <persName corresp="#p_SWH1">Sullivan</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_SWH1">William H.</persName> Secret; Personal Files
                        Only.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1968-01-22">January 22,
                            1968</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I talked with <persName>Bill Sullivan</persName> on Saturday, January 20. He
                    explained he thought we would be better off if the bombing [of North Vietnam]
                    were stopped in May, rather than now, since in Laos that was the beginning of
                    the rainy season which lasts until the autumn. The North Vietnamese trucks get
                    bogged down in Laos during this period and the roads are unusable.</p>
                <p>From Bill Sullivan’s standpoint, this idea has two values: <list>
                        <label>(1)</label>
                        <item>It automatically contributes to taking “no advantage” in Laos.</item>
                        <label>(2)</label>
                        <item>He is afraid if the bombing is stopped in the North during the dry
                            season, there will be a marked increase in bombing in Laos. This might
                            have adverse repercussions in our relations with <persName
                                corresp="#p_SPP1">Souvanna Phouma</persName> as well as make
                            Souvanna’s position of “neutrality” more difficult with Soviets and
                            others.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">
                            <hi rend="strong">W. Averell Harriman</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="2" xml:id="d328fn2">Printed from a copy that bears this typed
                            signature.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
